The day passed – day! There was no day; it had vanished as quickly as it had come – and night fell again; a night so long yet so brief; long in its terrible silence and brief in its fleeting hours.

A few years ago, I worked as a tutor in an after-school program for elementary school students. I did my best to help them in any subject they struggled with, though my strengths were in English and reading. One of the teachers recruited me to help a young boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who was having significant difficulties with reading. I realized something wasn't quite right; he was experiencing the most unusual problems. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, others not at all - it was quite puzzling. While he was clearly of Latino heritage, his spoken English was flawless. We continued to struggle until I met his mother. I was supervising a few remaining students while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when she came in. His mother spoke no English, only Spanish. Despite my limited Spanish knowledge (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. That's when it hit me like a thunderbolt: Adrian could read just fine - he simply wasn't familiar with the English alphabet. I'm not sure if this realization ultimately helped him, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier issues in schools, particularly in California, and to show that these challenges aren't always obvious. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can still be a major hurdle. While we all acknowledge this problem exists, what's the solution? For Adrian, the answer was relatively straightforward: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. However, for many children who barely speak English, the solution is far more complex. There's no single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutoring, ESL classes - none of these approaches alone will solve the problem. The key lies in combining all these methods!

First and foremost, the dual language system is an excellent approach - not just for native Spanish speakers, but for all children. Research shows that students in two-way bilingual education programs often outperform their peers academically. While some fear this approach wastes resources or won't benefit the majority of students, this is incorrect. If we implemented these programs as the standard rather than the exception, all children would benefit. But how do we achieve this? Should we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and impractical. However, there's no reason we couldn't have special aides or tutors who are bilingual.

From childhood on, most of us are told that there is something greater than ourselves, greater than we can comprehend. Some of us are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others go to temple or search within themselves for answers. Many of us readily accept the religions passed down to us by our parents. Others, however, reject them completely, denying that anything beyond knowing could exist in our own egocentric universe. We might adopt one set of values, only to later change our minds and replace it with another. Whatever path we choose, we journey to define a part of ourselves through our unique perspectives on spirituality. We search for a light in the darkness to guide us from the shadows into the sunlight.

"A cardinal," my father answered when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the front porch of our house, listening to the rain drumming on the tin roof above while smoking our cigarettes together. The gutters channeled the rain down, flooding the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain with a look that seemed half searching, half remembering. He had grown thinner in recent months, his clothes hanging loosely on his frame. His hair had thinned too, sparser than I remembered. He continued staring into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt lonely, frightened, and unable to tell my father how much I would miss him, because talking about it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer to his, and joined him in watching the falling rain in the June twilight.

My father died that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemotherapy and radiation hadn't eased his suffering, but had kept him alive several months beyond the doctors' predictions; I couldn't determine the value in merely prolonging his suffering. What kind of God would do this, I wondered. Alone in the night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I thought, He had long since stopped listening to me.

I hadn't wanted to watch him transition from this life to another. So I didn't. I couldn't bear to witness the ending of the life that had created mine. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family did, and knew Dad wouldn't want his only child to be a spectator to his death. I curled up in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of Republicanism. Although his primary occupation was farming, this profession combined with his brief political career shaped him into a man renowned for his commitment and candid expression on matters of personal liberty and governance. His devotion to an agricultural system formed the foundation for virtually all his views on government. His efforts to preserve and promote what he considered the most noble of all professions influenced his arguments on sovereignty, constitutional matters, and even the judicial system.

He believed that the United States had a unique opportunity to create an ideal system, free from the constraints of inherited traditions, thus enabling the establishment of true self-governance. Taylor held strong convictions about natural human rights, arguing that these rights were interconnected - if one was compromised, all would eventually fail, diminishing the value of those remaining. These rights, he maintained, should remain beyond government reach.

Taylor advocated for a government structure that acknowledged both the virtuous and corrupt aspects of human nature. His views on moral dualism were unwavering, asserting that since humans exercise government, all its virtues and vices must be human in nature. He identified positive principles as those protecting private property, advancing agriculture, and limiting capitalism, believing that a government founded on such principles would function justly regardless of its administration.

As a steadfast Republican of his era, Taylor advocated for strict constitutional interpretation. He favored a severely limited federal government, restricted to only those powers explicitly granted by the Constitution. He understood that an expansive federal government would be costly and prone to despotism. However, he cautioned against overly literal interpretation, arguing that understanding the founders' intent was crucial to prevent corruption. Notably, he regarded the Declaration of Independence as the nation's true charter, as it more clearly defined the country as a union of sovereign states rather than a single unified nation.

I gazed downward, my mind blankly processing the scene before me. With detached emotion and silence, with a practiced awareness that observed but refused to connect the subject to any abstract understanding, my mind analyzed the image before my eyes. Thoughts drifted in and out of my consciousness almost faster than they appeared. My mind worked so smoothly and efficiently that it seemed I had no thoughts of my own, just a fluid, active experience of what I was observing.

Once, following advice from an artist colleague, I bought an instructional book titled "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." Since I was six years old, I had wanted to learn to draw, and this book taught everything from understanding the basic nature of a pencil to how the brain processes lines. One technique the book teaches involves placing a square frame around any subject the artist wishes to study. This transforms an overwhelmingly complex scene - such as a fruit bowl on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room - into a manageable image: simply a bowl of fruit on a plain surface.

At that moment, looking down at the bowl before me, I couldn't mentally project that artist's frame. I was so overwhelmed, so struck by awe that I could only stand and stare in amazement. Picasso had his Blue Period, Monet cherished greenery, Italian Renaissance masters worked with a spectrum of colors. If I had any pretense of claiming my perspective as artistically worthy, here before me lay the beginning of my masterpiece, the start of my story: "Work in Brown."

My fingertips touched my chosen artistic tool, muscles tensed and relaxed as my hand moved through space, my mind's intention taking shape in what could have been my most creative moment. Water swirled, peaceful and smooth, crystal clear and pure. Particles broke away from the whole, carried away into nothingness. With muscles tensing, jerking more anxiously the second time, my hand struck the toilet handle again. The offensive brown mass refused to budge, stuck like a slug to the toilet bowl's bottom.

Standing with a mop loosely held, feet shoulder-width apart, green tie uncomfortably tight around my neck, I frowned slightly at the crude deposit of processed organic matter someone had left as a message for those unfortunate enough to clean the bathrooms at Rite Aid. After several more flushes and moments of quiet contemplation, my hand reached for the wall to my right, grabbed the end of the toilet paper, and began wrapping itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing straight, then bending at the waist, my hand descended slowly into the bowl, like a mother reaching into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are losing their lives behind the wheel. Multiple factors combine to create this deadly statistical pattern among America's youngest drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that one aspect of the problem lies in the fact that the adolescent brain is literally not prepared for the dangers of driving. Lack of experience is also at the core of the problem. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also results in higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding incidents, and road departures.

Teenagers face even greater risks when traveling with peers—something that anyone with common sense knows happens frequently. Research from the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center demonstrated a clear correlation between passenger age and accident frequency.

California and other states have tried to enhance teen driver safety by implementing provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and prohibit minor passengers. However, in my view, provisional licenses are merely temporary solutions. The fundamental issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical measures, simply unable to adequately manage the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even 18 is too young for a standard driver's license. According to USA Today, Zuckerman's research indicates a common tendency among those under 19-20 to seek thrills purely for the sensation.

It therefore makes sense to delay driving privileges until this thrill-seeking tendency begins to diminish. If we maintain our current practice of issuing licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to witness deadly accidents but likely see fatality numbers rise dramatically in coming years. By 2010, the children of Baby-Boomers will become eligible to drive, adding millions of new teen drivers to our roads.

Legislative action on this issue could be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue offering driver's education to prepare future drivers, but no one under 18 would be permitted to operate a motor vehicle. Provisional permits could still precede full licenses, and practical training requirements would remain in place. The required training hours could be standardized based on existing state requirements (California, for instance, currently mandates 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of supervised practice with an adult). Since teen driving statistics show concerning patterns across all states, uniform national legislation would be a reasonable and potentially effective approach to protecting young people nationwide.

This proposed legislation is not a groundbreaking concept.

This paper examines three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). Initially, it provides a concise definition of the disorder. Subsequently, it explains the diagnostic process, including common characteristics or "warning signs." The paper concludes by discussing methods through which teachers in mainstream classroom settings can support students with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), describes how effectively the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. In its specific definition, it refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the underlying neurobiological activity that generates electrophysiological auditory potentials. In simpler terms, it's a condition where the central nervous system (the brain) cannot properly process heard information. Individuals with CAPD have normal hearing capabilities and aren't considered hearing impaired; rather, the brain regions responsible for translating auditory input, distinguishing words, or separating conversation from background noise don't function typically.

The condition was first documented in the mid-1950s under the term "auditory imperception" during studies of children with communication disorders. Italian researchers Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing diagnostic tests in 1954. In 1961, Kimura introduced dichotic testing and proposed a model explaining the CANS physiology underlying dichotic perception. A significant national conference in 1977 sparked increased research into children with CAPD.

CAPD presents in various ways: affected individuals may struggle with sound localization; have trouble distinguishing between multiple sound events; face difficulties recognizing sound patterns; struggle to detect vocal nuances (such as sarcasm); experience auditory masking where one sound blocks another; have difficulty synthesizing sound information meaningfully; or struggle with sequencing auditory information.

Diagnosis requires systematic evaluation of listening behavior and performance on auditory function tests, conducted by professionals including audiologists, speech-language pathologists, and psychologists. The assessment may involve questionnaires, behavioral observations, and response monitoring to various stimuli. Currently, there isn't a single, universally accepted diagnostic tool with high success rates, and the disorder's cause remains unknown. Many diagnostic procedures involve presenting multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and asking patients to differentiate specific elements. Advanced diagnostic methods include measuring acoustic signal responses within the ear.

In pursuing my social work education, I aim to follow a career path with the Department of Family and Children Services to assist abused or neglected children and support troubled families. The values I can bring to social work include: service, respect, ethical conduct, dedication to improving relationships between others, and commitment to my own professional development to maintain competence in my field. These core values aren't just important for social workers; they're personally important to me.

I've always wanted to help others, though I was uncertain about my career path. During my high school and college years, I witnessed many people running from their problems, with some using less-than-ideal coping mechanisms. These experiences led me to pursue a Psychology degree. Still uncertain about my career direction, I decided to take a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy sitting on her couch. She explained he was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents' home. To offer help, I drove to his parents' house. There, I privately shared my concerns with the police and mentioned my Psychology degree. The police asked me to speak with the parents since legally they couldn't help the teenager. When I questioned the parents, they appeared nervous and made excuses, describing their son's "manipulative" behavior in involving outsiders in "simple" disputes. This experience led me to seriously consider a career in social work.

Another crucial value in social work is social justice. As a society, we claim to value individuality and mourn those we've lost, yet our concept of "individuality" often follows outdated traditions rather than embracing true uniqueness. If society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be like "everyone else"? I am an individual who dislikes imposing limitations on myself to conform. Throughout my academic years, I protested against social injustice through various means: dyeing my hair unconventional colors, wearing clothing that expressed my personality, getting multiple ear piercings, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and fighting against racism and discrimination whenever I encountered it. I believe in social justice and will continue to stand against social injustice.

This paper examines the biological and sociocultural models as they relate to the sleep disorder insomnia. The biological model emphasizes inherited genetic information and medical health aspects, while sociocultural models examine environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia examines these models and explains the selected research to better understand each model. The research findings and their explanations are then evaluated with respect to their specific strengths and limitations.

A sleep disorder may be classified as a primary sleep disorder, one related to another mental disorder, or one connected to other conditions. Primary sleep disorders are categorized as either Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while sleep disorders related to mental disorders are connected to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other sleep disorders may result from medical complications or substance use. The Dyssomnias include: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia involves difficulty in achieving or maintaining sleep, Primary Hypersomnia involves difficulty staying awake, both lasting at least one month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM. While Dyssomnias focus on sleep initiation and maintenance, Parasomnias involve behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological events during sleep. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to mental disorders involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review primarily focuses on insomnia and general primary sleep disorders in relation to biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genetic factors, hereditary elements, and physiologically acquired aspects. Neurons containing orexin in the hypothalamus regulate sleep and wakefulness. Research with mice has identified phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons that specifically control sleep/wake states. GABAA receptor activation promotes sleep responses, and its inhibition can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) was found to increase sleep duration. These findings suggest that mouse models may be applicable to human studies, indicating both genetic and environmental foundations for the GABAB receptor in humans. A dysfunction or absence of this receptor could impair natural sleep ability without medication. From a sociocultural perspective, if this phenotype is inherited, it could affect sleep regulation, and receptor alterations could naturally disturb sleep patterns, negatively impacting various life aspects including education, career, and daily activities requiring sustained attention and focus.

I've been studying here at University Park for about two and a half years now, equivalent to four and a half semesters. For many students, including myself, navigating the campus can be challenging. During my freshman year, I was assigned to a dorm in East Halls - practically at the easternmost edge of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. The journey from my room in Stuart Hall to classes in distant buildings like Willard, near campus center, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially in State College's frequently adverse weather conditions.

In conversation with a recent alumnus, I discovered that not long ago, East Halls was separated from the main campus by vast stretches of unused land. Today, that space has been filled with athletic fields, major new structures including the new Creamery and health services building, and is surrounded by apartment complexes. As our campus continues to grow, traveling between locations becomes increasingly challenging. What's the ideal solution to this mobility issue? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. However, bikes alone aren't the answer - students need to use them, and the campus infrastructure must accommodate cyclists' needs.

Recently, I spoke with a friend who had returned to cycling after several years away. He wondered why he'd ever stopped, saying, "Bikes are fantastic - there was a period when cycling wasn't considered cool, but it's really the most practical way to get around." Beyond its health benefits, cycling is the most efficient mode of transportation. A simple breakfast and some physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off-campus, just as far from the center as some dorms. Purchasing a bike was my wisest decision this year. I have daily classes in Thomas building, normally a twenty-five-minute walk from my residence. By bicycle, I can make this journey in just 5 minutes when riding quickly. The only challenge is that Pollock Road, while the most direct route to Thomas building from my home, isn't always easy to navigate, whether on bike or foot. While walking has its merits, my schedule is too demanding for that option. Without my bike, walking would be my only dependable means of getting to class. Walking to Thomas daily would consume an extra 30-40 minutes - that's over two and a half hours weekly. Factor in additional walking time for other classes and appointments, and it becomes an unsustainable time commitment.

Aldous Huxley critiques the looming threat of both technology and capitalistic structure through the creation of a dystopia in "Brave New World." In this world, community value supersedes individuality, and citizens are conditioned from birth to pursue instant gratification above all else. The population serves as unwitting pawns in a greater scheme, confined within an ideology dictated by the World Controller. When examining the work through a Marxist theoretical lens, the author's underlying concerns about these developing systems become apparent. Common Marxist concepts such as homogeneity and reification reinforce the notion that Huxley's novel comments on the flaws in his era's emerging economy.

Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist concept of false consciousness. The general population remains ignorant of true class relationships in economic terms, focused primarily on personal gain. This results from ideological control of the working class, clearly demonstrated through the conditioning of citizens in Brave New World. The lower classes - Delta, Gamma, and others - lack genuine free will; through hypnopaedia, their drive to consume, spend, and indulge is artificially enhanced. The World Controller manipulates this dynamic. Hegemony - the complete domination of social classes by a select group - is evidently at work. Lower classes remain oblivious to this manipulation, literally buying into an ideology that perpetuates the system. Upper classes possess awareness but remain passive; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard take meaningful action. Indeed, class interactions strongly indicate capitalism's perceived oppression.

Genuine interpersonal relationships are absent in Brave New World. Characters lack individual depth, even among principal figures. Huxley appears to suggest that the combined rise of technology and capitalism strips humanity of free will and expression. Love and extreme emotions are nonexistent; instead, interactions remain superficial, illustrated by men's focus on women's physical attributes ("pneumatic" qualities) and women's casual discussion of their encounters. Moreover, each social class's acceptance of their hierarchical position reflects capitalism's socioeconomic impact. Their unwavering commitment to community roles mirrors Marxist views on the proletariat, who are falsely convinced of their superiority as long as they continue consuming, obeying, and conforming to peer expectations.

Nearly four years ago, I enrolled in an Islamic studies course at CBC. One of the main topics of heated debate in the class was whether Islam could be considered a hostile religion. I believe this question is even more pertinent today than ever before. Looking back at events since 9/11, I have personally witnessed mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme form of tolerance towards Islam in America. I doubt that in 2001 we could have imagined a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who has clear Muslim connections in his family history.

The Prophet's Biography fascinates me because, based on my understanding of Muhammad's history, the biography seems to contradict his actual personality. From my previous knowledge and studies, I understood that Muhammad forced conversions to Islam, conquering tribes and compelling them to adopt the Islamic faith. However, the biography portrays him as something of a martyr, misunderstood by others and displaying humility, after which people gradually came to recognize the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

Furthermore, there are remarkable parallels between Jesus' ministry and Muhammad's 'miracles.' The most striking example is when he supposedly multiplied mutton and milk to feed more than forty men abundantly. This writing style suggests to me that the authors wanted to present Muhammad as a humble prophet who needed not prove anything but simply lived in truth and miracles. This kind of narrative particularly troubles me as it appears to diminish Jesus Christ's miracles and life, almost as if they're attempting to appropriate Jesus' characteristics through Muhammad.

The biography contains numerous accounts that seem intended to provide 'witness testimony' or examples of people who 'independently' converted to Islam. However, these stories often come from third-hand or even more removed sources, with narratives beginning "heard from someone who heard from someone else." Rather than strengthening their credibility, I found this approach undermined the stories' authenticity and made them appear more questionable.

What disturbs me most about this work is its attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly, humble, endearing, wise, and gentle individual. Historical accounts seem to contradict this portrayal of Muhammad as a gentle and humble man, and I can't help but wonder if modern Muslims are aware of the true historical context of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and his convictions during his lifetime were quickly abandoned in the evolution of Christian thought following his death. Looking at this history in broad terms, we see Christianity trending increasingly away from its origins. Today's world demonstrates a growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive inclination. While traditionalists remain and will resist thinking beyond their taught beliefs, this segment of the population may not be influential enough to shape the whole.

Among Christians, historical consciousness will greatly expand in the coming years. A desire will emerge to separate later Christian doctrinal additions from the original intentions of the religion's founder. Though it may take generations or centuries, the outcome appears inevitable: A great reversal in Christian historical trends will occur. There will be a return to its original form. A movement will grow that systematically removes layers of doctrine, as if turning back time, until only Jesus's original divine message to humanity remains, stripped of later interpretations.

When this movement sweeps through America and Europe, inspiring masses to worship as in Jesus's time, following only his teachings, the church as an institution will remain strong as a guiding force. However, as theological understanding reverts, Christianity's extreme denominational diversity will consolidate toward unified belief and practice. Instead of differences between regions, denominations, and divisions, we will see increasing commonality.

History has witnessed great reversals before - from Christians being persecuted by Rome to the Empire becoming Christian, from slavery to African-American leadership. The coming religious reversion will unfold within Christianity, undoing historical accumulations in search of its source, while reducing diversity. Crucially, this process will be enabled by reading Jesus's words metaphorically rather than literally.

Looking back far enough, we find only Judaism as Christianity's theological foundation. Monotheism, divine revelation, and the authority of Hebrew scriptures were central to the religion when Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 BCE. The Jewish population was divided among Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and the common majority.

I believe that "The Jungle" demonstrates how humans are inherently greedy and self-centered at their core. They only want to take care of themselves and make their lives as comfortable as possible, while never considering those beneath them. "The Jungle" illustrates this in numerous ways. The most obvious example can be found in the owners and managers of the large factories. Their sole desire is to make their companies and factories as large and impressive as possible. They show no concern for anyone or anything that stands in their way or gets harmed by their progress.

According to Upton Sinclair's work, the factory buildings created a stark silhouette against the sky, with massive chimneys releasing endless streams of smoke into the atmosphere. Sinclair paints a vivid picture of the devastating environmental damage being caused. He reveals that the owners have absolutely no regard for any person or animal that might suffer harm. They remain indifferent to the thick smoke pouring from their factories or the animal waste running off from the countless pens throughout Packingtown.

The owners and managers showed equal disregard for the workers who made them wealthy. They would do anything to increase profits or cut costs, creating an environment where "from top to bottom, the place is merely a boiling cauldron of jealousies and hatred; loyalty and decency are nowhere to be found, and human worth is measured solely against the dollar." Workers could be dismissed without notice, leaving them without compensation or assistance in finding new employment. During this period, there were few if any laws protecting workers' safety or welfare, allowing management to operate unchecked, forcing employees to increase productivity while working in deplorable conditions. The residents of Packingtown were expected to endure these horrible conditions both at work and in their living environments, though this was never explicitly stated. No organizations existed to support or inform the working class, and while unions formed, they often exploited rather than helped the poor workers. The workers were so mistreated and trapped within Packingtown's system that they were likened to slaves, existing in a state of near-starvation and completely dependent on the whims of men just as brutal as historical slave drivers.

Dream-land is considered one of Edgar Allan Poe's self-proclaimed superior poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thule," which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term in reference to an island north of Britain that the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. Poe had a strong interest in German authors.

This connection is significant as it demonstrates Poe's familiarity with Goethe's work. In his book "Poe's Politian and Goethe's Mignon," Karl J. Arndt comments on the similarity between their poems and concludes that Poe was emulating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature describes Goethe as a celebrated author of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts - the first in 1808 and the second in Goethe's death year, 1832. Within the second part of Faust lies a short poem titled "The King of Thule." The poem tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet as a gift. Following her death, he begins drinking heavily and weeping for his dead queen. Eventually, he decides it's time to die, gives away his possessions to his children except for the goblet. He then walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies.

Under California law, a customer who was injured after slipping on spilled applesauce in a grocery store might be entitled to punitive damages by demonstrating that the store manager acted with malice, given that he was informed twice about the spill but failed to have it cleaned for thirty minutes because he was eating dinner.

The judge is unlikely to summarily dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify such damages, a plaintiff must demonstrate that the defendant's actions showed willful and conscious disregard for probable harm, while also proving the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have anticipated the likely harm of leaving a spill uncleaned, especially since multiple D&D customers had been injured from similar incidents in previous months. While her argument about Martin's actions being despicable may be less compelling, it remains reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009, yet Martin still failed to take appropriate safety measures.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 PM, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin, who was on his dinner break, claimed he "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 PM, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also reported the spill, receiving the same response. At 5:30 PM, plaintiff Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. Five other slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D during 2009. Palmer is now pursuing both compensatory and punitive damages, and we are evaluating whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

Under California law, a plaintiff may recover punitive damages for non-contractual obligations if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud or malice" (Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010)). The statute defines malice as either intentional harmful conduct or "despicable" behavior committed with "willful and conscious disregard for others' rights or safety." Courts have interpreted malicious conduct as actions taken with conscious disregard when the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of their conduct, and willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences" (Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979)).

She had always sensed something was missing in her life. It was an unfulfillable longing that persisted. It began when she was around 14, just entering her teenage years, and remained with her three years later at 17. By then, she had realized she was searching for someone rather than something. Yet she felt no attraction to boys. Several had been drawn to her, making awkward attempts to court the uncourtable, but none sparked her interest. She often questioned this peculiar situation, trying to understand what could cause such an unusual circumstance in a teenage girl. Years of reflection had produced theories, but none substantial enough to seriously consider. So she continued living, constantly questioning her desires.

A day at home was typically peaceful. Her parents were gentle, composed people who never quarreled with each other and, surprisingly, rarely argued with their daughter. Their only conflicts arose from her assertions of independence and free spirit. Though born to serene parents, she balanced their energy with her vibrant and engaging personality, making her well-liked, especially combined with her inherent kindness.

This day, however, was different. As she wandered from room to room, seeking fresh inspiration, she heard her mother's beautiful voice release a sharp scream from the kitchen. She rushed in, panic rising, calling out, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She found her mother on the floor, clearly in pain, taking short, pained breaths. Her mother managed to say between gasps, "Ouch... honey, I... need you to take me to... the hospital." The words came out strained, and her daughter could see she was in severe pain. "Okay Mom, just show me where I can lift you." Her mother guided her hands, and at that moment, the household's hero was thankful for her strength training classes. She carried her mother to the car, carefully laid her in the back seat, and drove.

The hospital visit brought typical scents of antiseptic and illness, tinged with anxiety. But she barely noticed, focused entirely on helping her mother. She carried her injured mother in swiftly, calling for medical assistance. Concerned staff quickly gathered, transferring her mother onto a gurney. They whisked her away for immediate examination, leaving her daughter to wait in worried solitude.

The incident had occurred when her mother fell from a stepstool while trying to reach a vase in the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as measured by a high "alternative Mediterranean (aMed) diet score", correlates with a lower risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke-related mortality. The aMed diet represents a modified version of the Mediterranean diet, characterized by increased consumption of plant-based foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but encompassing fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (in preference to saturated fats) and fish, while limiting animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is permitted.

Previous prospective studies have documented an inverse relationship between Mediterranean diet adherence and overall cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. An intervention trial demonstrated the Mediterranean diet's superiority over a low-fat diet in achieving weight reduction and improving the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese subjects. Earlier research had not specifically addressed stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological investigation tracked 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without prior CVD or diabetes history, who participated in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study involving 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. Between 1984 and 2004, researchers calculated aMed diet scores six times using self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to evaluate nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of nurses maintained participation throughout the 20-year study period. FFQs underwent validation studies, and reported cases of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were verified through medical records, hospital documentation, autopsies, or death certificates. When records were unavailable, cases were designated as "probable" and included, accounting for approximately 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions.

To minimize random individual variation and better represent long-term dietary patterns, researchers calculated cumulative averages of the aMed scores from repeated FFQs. The study accounted for potential confounding factors by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, hormone replacement therapy, multivitamin use, alcohol consumption, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Using Cox proportional-hazard modeling, researchers evaluated the relationship between aMed scores and CHD and stroke risk, employing separate models for fatal and nonfatal events.

Higher adherence to the Mediterranean diet, indicated by elevated aMed diet scores, was associated with reduced risk of both CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up period, researchers documented 2,391 cases of CHD, 1,763 stroke cases, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths. Women in the highest aMed quintile demonstrated a 29% lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

The sign reads "Hitler lives in Burma."

Ellen Page, the Juno star, stands alone at a street corner, holding a cardboard sign above her head with this disturbing message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian nation under the control of a brutal military junta that seized power through a coup in 1962. In 2007, the country witnessed its first public demonstrations in ten years. These protests, led primarily by Burmese monks, became known as "The Saffron Revolution," named after the monks' traditional robe color. As initial protests grew, public participation increased. While the Burmese authorities initially tolerated the monks' peaceful gatherings, the situation soon escalated into what many described as open warfare between the monastery and military, with forces raiding temples nationwide. Foreign journalists faced immediate arrest, and on September 27th, 2007, Japanese photographer Kenji Nagai was killed simply for documenting a protest. Though official figures cite 13 deaths, defected Colonel Hla Win revealed, "The true death toll reaches thousands - far more than reported."

This pattern of oppression is hardly new. Throughout history, governments have sought to suppress dissent and maintain absolute control. Ancient Roman emperors claimed divine right to rule absolutely. Japanese emperors were viewed as living gods, supposedly guiding their people toward prosperity through modern innovations and traditional practices, while our current president, George W. Bush, maintains close ties with Ted Haggard, who leads an influential conservative religious organization.

Notable examples include the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests, where students, intellectuals, and workers demonstrated against government authoritarianism. Death toll estimates vary dramatically - from the government's claim of 200-300 to the Chinese Red Cross's estimate of 2,000-3,000. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s saw Hutu militias, backed by their government, systematically eliminate Tutsis and moderate politicians regardless of ethnicity. Hitler's Third Reich, which spanned years and nations, systematically persecuted and murdered Jewish people, standing as another extreme example of state-sponsored violence.

Duke Ellington's jazz legacy stems largely from his longevity and, consequently, his creative ability to shape his orchestra. While his piano presence remains subtle in many compositions, his brilliance as a composer shone through in creating rich, complex pieces that highlighted the individual talents of his band members. Ellington masterfully crafted frameworks that allowed soloists to improvise freely while also writing tightly orchestrated passages that leveraged each band member's unique style to emphasize musical ideas. In doing so, he enhanced the orchestra's overall tone, creating distinctive and original sounds for each piece. His deep understanding of individual players' sounds and how they harmonized within the growing ensemble enabled him to compose some of jazz history's most innovative and brilliant works.

The Grove Music dictionary notes Ellington's innovative use of voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career, with Creole Love Call serving as an early example. This twelve-bar blues piece, structured in six distinct choruses, demonstrates his ability to complement soloists' styles and use vocals to add texture without lyrics. His innovative approach continues in works like Hot and Bothered and It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing), where he masterfully combines tight orchestration with rich tonal colors, often blending instrumental and vocal elements to create unique, complementary sounds.

Why do organisms evolve in the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D'Arcy Thompson noted in 1917 that "even now zoologists have barely begun to dream of defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," the same holds true today. In recent times, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk shell formation through both individual development and evolutionary history (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our research examines how mathematical modeling of developmental and evolutionary changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can help illuminate the mechanisms driving the direction and extent of evolutionary-developmental changes.

A shell can be understood as a tube-like structure that travels through 360 degrees of space over time. These rotations or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the shell's central column, known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls expand can vary, and a continuous line called the suture separates each whorl. In most shells, the final whorl (body whorl) is the largest. The spire comprises all whorls except the last one. The apex marks the spire's tip, while the opposite end is the base. The animal extends from its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be examined from apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural perspectives. (The "standard" orientation shows the shell in an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upward.)

To count whorls, one should first view the shell from above (apical view) and locate where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and can be measured to the nearest quarter whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures moving through time and space as the animal builds its shell. It's possible to track the aperture's path using coordinates of each whorl's aperture center and its horizontal and vertical radii. This trajectory can be represented both graphically and mathematically, allowing for parameter variation and modification of mollusk shell formation patterns.

The infant and child mortality rate in Indonesia has remained largely unchanged over the past decade. While the country is progressing toward achieving many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation targets, the improvement rates for child and maternal health fall far short of the necessary advances needed to reach their targets by 2015. The various reasons for these deficiencies are discussed below and indicate the necessity to strengthen the healthcare system rather than focusing on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has shown progress in increasing the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now meeting this standard. However, this category still includes traditional practitioners, such as midwives, who cannot provide medical interventions in cases of complicated pregnancies (explaining the high percentage of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage). In essence, the improvements shown in this particular indicator are somewhat deceptive, and considerable work remains to be done. Furthermore, there has been a decrease in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five being treated by healthcare professionals. While postnatal care data is incomplete, it's evident that this area is also problematic, with low rates throughout the country.

Cesarean section rates remain lower than expected, at approximately 4%. These rates also highlight another concerning disparity: while urban areas show a 7% c-section rate, rural areas only show 2%. This demonstrates the inequitable distribution of healthcare services across the country, with access clearly concentrated in urban areas. Another access issue involves vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and wealthiest quintiles. The poor evidently face greater difficulties accessing healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket expenses.

In considering next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the fundamental question is how to most effectively address the service gap. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing exclusively on pre- and post-pregnancy care? While programmatic approaches to address the aforementioned problems are appealing, as they offer more targeted, manageable objectives and typically generate faster results, there are important drawbacks to consider. A major concern is that heavy investment in one particular health sector often depletes funding for other areas and attracts human resources to the better-funded sector (as seen in the impact of international HIV/AIDS funding on family planning). Additionally, running multiple parallel programs leads to service duplication and lack of coordination, resulting in increased bureaucracy for supplies and funding.

The categorization of popular music has expanded so dramatically over the past century that it now encompasses such a vast array of genres that creating a definitive list has become challenging. Adding to this complexity, most if not all genres - including rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, to name just a few - have generated multiple sub-genres and even further subdivisions within their domains. The sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has arguably emerged as one of the most diverse and expressive forms of popular music in the last four decades. Its expressiveness stems from its ability to convey a wide range of emotions, though these tend to gravitate toward the darker end of the emotional spectrum. Its diversity became apparent shortly after the genre's inception, when people began to recognize its inherent flexibility and started creating their own sub-genres, which in turn led to further subdivisions, a process that continues to evolve today.

Several decades before the Surrealist artists began creating their dream-like works, the artist Henri Rousseau was already carefully shaping his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. "The Dream," a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman overwhelmed by the wonders of the land she visits in a dream but also Rousseau's own personal dreams and aspirations as a painter. From the beginning of his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists and art enthusiasts, finding himself faced with a difficult internal dilemma in pursuing this goal. "The Dream" is Henri Rousseau's work that best reflects his lifelong inner struggle: whether to conform to or imitate certain painting styles to gain acceptance from the critical art world he so admired, or to allow himself to develop creatively independent and unique, forging his own path as he went along.

Before analyzing The Dream from this perspective, one must be familiar with Rousseau's life story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwestern France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware merchant who enjoyed middle-class prosperity. Having received no formal artistic training in his youth, he worked until the age of forty as a gabelou for France, a municipal toll collector, though he was mistakenly nicknamed douanier, a customs inspector. The death of his first wife, Clémence, following the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with just one surviving child, a daughter named Julia, and profound grief. He sought refuge in a new life and turned to painting for solace and fresh beginnings. Unlike his contemporaries who romanticized peasant life in their paintings, Rousseau was essentially a folk painter who embodied the hopes and dreams of his social class.

Many great thinkers have proposed a deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this connection. As John Keats expresses in "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty - that is all you know on earth, and all you need to know." Much of our life's knowledge comes through education or experience. Yet, as Keats suggests, our appreciation of ethics and aesthetics seems to develop without these conventional teaching methods.

Both ethics and aesthetics aim to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are largely attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature moves us, or why an action is considered moral, rather than providing rigid rules for judging or creating good art or ethical behavior.

More fundamentally, criticism of art or morality can never fully capture the essence of what is good or beautiful. While we might discuss the Mona Lisa in terms of technique, composition, or cultural context, these elements alone don't explain its artistic merit. People often preface their analysis of favorite artworks or literature with "There's just something about it" before delving into more detailed explanations. I believe both art and morality resist complete reduction to their component qualities. As Flannery O'Connor notes, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." Something transcendent remains beyond even the most thorough analysis of literature, and I believe ethics shares this quality. As Wittgenstein observes, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." This ineffable quality, this je ne sais quoi, represents the most powerful attribute of both art and morality, creating a bridge between them.

I believe morality and art are so intimately connected because we experience both most powerfully at a noumenal level, to use Kant's terminology. They affect us in ways we can experience but never fully explain. This connection is particularly strong in literature. As McKean observes, literature's distinct quality among the arts lies in its moral dimension. While moral standards might not apply to all arts, such as music, they are as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living inherently involves values, and literature's significance stems precisely from the values we discover within it.

Today's Germany is regarded as a powerful force, a unified nation with its own unique cultural blend stretching from the shadows of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This same culture can be experienced from Cologne on the Rhine, through Germany's heartland, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe River. Given such a distinctive culture, it's not surprising that the Germany we know today emerged from various sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral homeland of the German people. The origin of this name remains heavily debated among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed the name came from a Germanic tribe then known as the Tungrians, who had previously been called Germans before crossing the Rhine and engaging in battle with Gallic forces. Julius Caesar first employed the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and fought against Germanic tribes who frequently crossed the Rhine with hostile intentions. He adopted this word from the Gauls themselves, using it to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he had not.

The early Roman historian Tacitus documented in his 98 AD work "On the Origin and Situation of the Germans" that these people appeared to be indigenous and unmixed with other races through migration or interaction. He noted that ancient migrants typically arrived by sea rather than by land, questioning who would choose to leave Asia or Africa for Germany, with its wild landscape, harsh climate, and austere character, unless it was already their homeland.

And who indeed would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not initially. They would conduct expeditions into Germanic territories for goods and occasional land campaigns, but ultimately they mostly returned to their vast empire. As Germanic tribes emerged in the mid-first century, they lived along the borders of the Roman Empire, trading their local goods and offering their services within the ranks of the Roman army.

The play Twelfth Night appears to suggest that while disguise can serve as a useful tool for sustained deception, one must ultimately shed this artificial persona or risk losing their authentic self in the process. A significant challenge in ending such deception lies in the potential alienation it may cause. Thus, one faces a crucial choice between preserving their true identity and maintaining relationships with others. While some might react indifferently to learning they've been deceived, others will take offense at the masquerade.

The matter of gender-based deception proves particularly complex, raising numerous secondary concerns, chief among them being the motivation. What drives someone to abandon their genuine identity and assume the disguise of another gender? In Viola's situation, self-preservation clearly motivates her actions, as evidenced when she states: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count..."

Finding herself in unfamiliar territory, Viola adopts a male persona for protection, though this choice isolates her from potential female allies and support. Her convincing performance as a man leads to complicated romantic entanglements, with Olivia mistaking her for Sebastian ("Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.") and suppressed romantic tension with Orsino ("Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.")

While contemporary readers might view this progressively, Twelfth Night can be interpreted as demonstrating how deception can catalyze the revelation of hidden emotions, particularly regarding Olivia and Orsino. The text suggests these characters may harbor unexplored subconscious desires that Viola/Cesario's presence forces them to confront. However, Olivia's quick transition of affections from Cesario to Sebastian, and her eventual acceptance of Viola as family ("A sister, you are she") suggests that Shakespeare may be satirizing those who judge purely on appearances rather than exploring deeper themes of gender identity.

German colonial rule has been criticized by various observers for its brutality, particularly regarding the genocide of the Herero and Nama people in German South West Africa. Naturally, such a vast colonial empire cannot be characterized by such a simple description alone. The German colonial empire exhibited as much diversity in its policies and governance styles as it did in its geography. Educational opportunities across the colonies showed similar variation. When the British assumed control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they encountered a substantial population of educated and literate Africans. German educational initiatives in Cameroon and other colonies also received praise from contemporary writers.

The situation in South West Africa (modern-day Namibia) stood in marked contrast. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and took an active role in native education, in South West Africa the education of indigenous peoples was delegated almost entirely to missionary societies with minimal government support. The government did, however, invest considerably in European education in the colony, establishing state schools and providing stronger support and oversight for missionary schools serving white settlers. These educational policies left lasting impacts on South West Africa, even after German rule ended. While other German colonies could boast significant numbers of educated African populations, in South West Africa, the vast majority of indigenous people remained uneducated and illiterate. Various social, political, and economic factors contributed to South West Africa's divergent experience. This study aims to broaden the discussion by identifying these factors, with particular emphasis on new research regarding settler and colonial authority attitudes toward native Africans.

A considerable body of literature exists concerning education in the German colonial empire. Most sources are in German, written during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. Early works primarily focused on describing colonial educational systems. Later English-language scholarship expanded the discourse through comparative analyses and detailed examinations of specific educational aspects. These studies revealed significant variations between different colonies' educational systems. Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa stands as the most notable work directly addressing this paper's topic. Cohen's comparative analysis of the two colonies' educational systems attributes many of South West Africa's distinctive educational features to its large settler population.

Compared to Germany's other colonial territories, South West Africa enjoyed a relatively temperate climate, despite much of its territory being arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these more hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites resided in South West Africa, while East Africa, the colony with the next largest settler population, had only 5,336 European inhabitants.

The United States of America and Mexico exemplify two nations that were once characterized by an enduring rivalry spanning 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The pinnacle of this rivalry manifested in the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States attacked and conquered Mexico, securing Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other confrontations occurred between the two nations, finally subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry originated from American and Mexican conflicts over fundamental issues including religion, culture, and tradition, coupled with significant clashes of material interests.

This pattern mirrors many other nations experiencing enduring rivalries with their neighbors. Countries sharing borders typically face conflicting interests that foster rival positions between them. The United States and Mexico's situation parallels many other enduring rivalries between nations sharing common borders. As David M. Pletcher (1977) notes, "Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems." Indeed, both nations' proximity to the United States contributed to their rival status, while other Latin American nations have maintained generally positive relations with the United States.

Religious differences created a divide between the two nations, a common historical pattern among many countries. Sally Frahm (2001) observes that "if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy." Similar to how the Cold War rivalry between the United States and Soviet Union combined ideological struggles with competition over vital interests, this rivalry centered on religious rather than political differences. This mistrust evolved from historical English-Spanish tensions, with both nations inheriting prejudices from their former colonial powers, significantly hampering the development of friendly diplomatic relations.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) document 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most conflicts during this time involved territorial issues, particularly border raids from Mexican territory and other frontier-related problems. Bandit and outlaw attacks on American border towns remained problematic until both nations established stronger military presence along their borders.

According to Schmitt (1974), the rivalry began to diminish as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" and ultimately concluded when American interests "shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico" during the latter part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply rooted need for safety and security that I lacked as a child. "You'll always find work; people will always get sick" was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I grew through adolescence and beyond. So - although my dream was to be a scientist or journalist - preferably both - I chose nursing.

Nevertheless, there I was: 46 years old, single, with barely any savings and unable to work. To this day I remain disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I literally have nothing left to call my own. I get by, but each day is a struggle that challenges my security, safety, and self-worth. While nothing in my life is certain anymore, one truth remains clear: I couldn't have survived these years without the support of my family and a few good friends, regardless of how strong I was. And trust me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that life will always bring emergencies - both big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well-prepared you are, some challenges are simply too great to face alone.

I completely agree that we in the U.S. need to stop placing all our trust in big government's "basket" - heaven knows it's already moldy and crumbling. However, I'd much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again - learning to help each other and ask for help - rather than watching everyone retreat to their backyards to build individual fallout shelters.

American Conservatives speak of the "rugged individualism" that built this country, but in truth, what sustained our ancestors through hard times wasn't rugged individualism - it was compassion, mutual respect, and shared resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't reach the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit with first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting with duct tape for windows in case of a biological attack. I have multiple flashlights, various batteries, plenty of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods too. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and can preserve your own food - do it. It's an excellent idea, as is having a wood stove, provided you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're doing all that, make sure to get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he renounced worldly matters and achieved enlightenment, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—with its most orthodox branch known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion, now approximately twenty-five centuries old, appears quite different today than it did during Buddha's lifetime. This is evident everywhere, for example in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where an annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds religious significance, despite Buddha never having taught about such festivities. These differences span from superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.

Several qualifying terms are essential to this discussion. There is the concept of internal versus external forces. An internal force is defined as one originating from members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of their monastic status. An external force comes from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community—arising from a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force neither wishes to help nor harm the Buddhist community—though it may inadvertently do either. These terms will be referenced frequently throughout this discussion.

First, it is crucial to examine the fundamentals of the religion—the doctrines at the heart of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma essentially comprises the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains Buddhism's metaphysical components. The metaphysical concepts include Anatta (no-self), Dukkha (inherent suffering in life), and Anicca (impermanence of all things). Only by understanding these concepts can one end Sansara, the continuous cycle of death and rebirth. Along with Sansara will end lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) when one achieves enlightenment. The Vinaya Pitaka establishes rules for living. For laypeople, there are five precepts (abstaining from killing, lying, stealing, sexual misconduct, and intoxicating substances). Monks must follow many more disciplinary rules. The most fundamental doctrinal concept in Buddhism is the four noble truths: first, Dukkha—the truth that life is suffering; second, that attachment causes suffering; third, that suffering can be overcome.
